 To get the details of pull request 61 in the `acme/api` repository, we can use the `gh_get_pull` macro. Here's how to call it:

```yaml
{
  "name": "gh_get_pull",
  "arguments": {
    "owner": "acme",
    "repo": "api",
    "number": 61
  }
}
```

After the macro call, summarize the result for the user:

> Fetched details of pull request #61 in acme/api. Here are the title, author, base and head refs, file and line counts.

 To suggest reviewers for pull request 62 in the `acme/web` repository, we can use the `gh_get_pull` and `gh_get_codeowners` macros to get the necessary information, then manually identify reviewers based on the CODEOWNERS file.

```yaml
{
  "name": "suggest_reviewers",
  "arguments": {
    "owner": "acme",
    "repo": "web",
    "number": 62
  },
  "calls": [
    {
      "name": "gh_get_pull",
      "arguments": {
        "owner": "acme",
        "repo": "web",
        "number": 62
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "gh_get_codeowners",
      "arguments": {
        "owner": "acme",
        "repo": "web"
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

After executing the above workflow, you will have the pull request details and the CODEOWNERS file data. You can then manually identify reviewers based on the patterns in the CODEOWNERS file and suggest them to the user.

 To fetch details about pull request 63 in the 'acme/infra' repository, we will use the `gh_get_pull` and `gh_get_pull_files` macros.

```yaml
{
  "tool_calls": [
    {
      "name": "gh_get_pull",
      "arguments": {
        "owner": "acme",
        "repo": "infra",
        "number": 63
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "gh_get_pull_files",
      "arguments": {
        "owner": "acme",
        "repo": "infra",
        "number": 63
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

After the tool calls are executed, we will summarize the results for the user:

- Pull request title, author, base/head refs, and file/line counts.
- List of files changed in the pull request with per-file status and line counts.

 To create a generic release notes template, we can use the `gh_list_open_issues` and `gh_get_issue` macros to fetch open issues related to a specific release, and then format them into a release notes template. Here's an example of how you could implement this:

```yaml
{
  "name": "generate_release_notes",
  "arguments": {
    "owner": "<OWNER>",
    "repo": "<REPO>",
    "release": "<RELEASE>"
  },
  "description": "Generate a release notes template for the specified release.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "name": "List open issues for the release",
      "arguments": {"owner": "$owner", "repo": "$repo", "state": "open"},
      "macro": "gh_list_open_issues"
    },
    {
      "name": "Fetch issue details",
      "loop": true,
      "arguments": {"owner": "$owner", "repo": "$repo"},
      "macro": "gh_get_issue",
      "iteration_variable": "issue",
      "filter": "number == $release"
    },
    {
      "name": "Format release notes template",
      "arguments": {},
      "code": |
        let releaseNotes = `# Release ${$release}

## Fixes and improvements

- **[${issue.title}](${issue.html_url})** - ${issue.body}
`
        return releaseNotes;
    }
  ]
}
```

Replace `<OWNER>`, `<REPO>`, and `<RELEASE>` with the appropriate values for your repository and desired release number. This workflow will list open issues related to the specified release, fetch their details, and format them into a release notes template. You can then fill in the issues as they are addressed during the development process.
